'''Quintueles''' (variant: '''San Clemente de Quintueles''') is one of 41 [[parish (administrative division)|parishes]] in [[Villaviciosa, Asturias|Villaviciosa]], a [[municipality]] within the province and [[autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous community]] of [[Asturias]], in northern [[Spain]]. {{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
Situated at {{convert|88|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[above mean sea level|above sea level]], the ''[[Parroquia (Spain)|parroquia]]'' is {{convert|9.81|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} in area, with a population of 663 ([[Instituto Nacional de Estadística (Spain)|INE]] 2008).
Fossilised [[pterosaur]] [[Trace fossil|tracks]] have been uncovered at Quintueles' [[Lastres Formation]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Avanzini|first=M |author2=J C Garcia-Ramos |author3=J Lires |author4=M Menegon |author5= L Pinuela |year=2005|title=Turtle tracks from the Late Jurassic of Asturias, Spain|journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica|publisher=Panstwowe Wydawn. Naukowe|location=Warszawa |volume=50|issue=4|pages=743–755|issn=0567-7920|oclc=108032879|url=http://www.app.pan.pl/archive/published/app50/app50-743.pdf}}</ref>
==Climate== The climate of Quintueles is oceanic, humid and generally temperate.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
==Cuisine== [[Fabes de la Granja|Spanish beans]] are produced in great quantities in Quintueles. These Spanish beans, along with the local fish and shellfish, comprise the staple foods of the region. Popular dishes include Spanish beans with [[clam]]s, [[sea urchin]]s, [[goose barnacle]]s, [[Crangon crangon|brown shrimp]], [[velvet crab]]s, [[European spider crab]]s, [[conger|conger eels]], and [[Whiting (fish)|whiting]].<!-- "barbaes" is listed as a food too. This must be Asturian. What is the English equivalent? I can't determine it. --> The local [[cider]] is also produced in abundance.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
==Cultural heritage== [[File:Playa La Ñora 2017.jpg|thumb|La Ñora beach.]] [[Playa de La Ñora]], a local beach, is a major attraction in the area. Quintueles' granaries, villages and farms produce the apples and [[Fabes de la Granja|Spanish beans]] that the community is known for.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
Also worth mentioning are the local sandstone quarries. Folklore states that a fifteenth-century hermitage was situated among the quarries. Upon paying homage to the [[Virgin of the Snows]], the hermit was said to have received the protection of a large oak tree for his dwelling. The neighbourhood where this oak tree stood was named "Granderroble" in observance of the legend.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
==Directions to Quintueles== Beginning from [[Gijón]], take the A-8 toward [[Santander, Cantabria|Santander]] and leave at junction 378 for Quintueles. On entering the town, bear left at the intersection with the N-632. After 200 metres, turn right onto highway VV-I in the direction of [[Playa de la Ñora]]. After two kilometres is Quintueles' school and church, which are an important part of the community. Another option is to follow the N-632 road towards [[Villaviciosa, Asturias|Villaviciosa]]. Shortly after passing the installation of [[Llorea]] is the council of Gijón. Continue past Villaviciosa to arrive in the town of Quintueles. After three more kilometres the route reaches the bypass to Playa de la Ñora. Quintueles is approximately 10 kilometres from Gijón.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
==Festivals==
{| class="wikitable" |- ! Date ! Spanish Name ! English Name |- | April | [[Gastronómico de la Llámpara]]. | Cuisine of the Lamp. |- | Aug. 5 | [[Fiesta de Granderroble]]. | Festival of the Large Oak Tree. |- | Aug. 5 | [[Fiesta de la Virgen de las Nieves]]. | Festival of the Virgin of the Snows. |- | Aug. 24 | [[Fiesta de San Bartolomé]]. | Festival of Saint Bartholomew. |- | Nov. 23 | [[Fiesta de San Clemente]]. | Festival of Saint Clement. |}
Cuisine of the Lamp ([[Gastronómico de la Llámpara]]), is a festival organized by the Trumpet Society of Cultural Recreation ([[Sociedad Cultural Recreativa Clarín]]) of a neighbouring municipality, [[Quintes]]. The festival is hosted by the townsfolk of both Quintueles and Quintes.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
== Location == Quintueles is situated on the [[flat coast]] of [[Spain|Spain's]] [[Cantabrian Sea]]. It is approximately 19 kilometres from [[Villaviciosa, Asturias|Villaviciosa]] and 12 kilometres from [[Gijón]]. Quintueles is a coastal town with beautiful, tall cliffs that overlook the Cantabrian Sea. Quintueles currently has a population of 663 people and there are about 460 dwellings. The town has an area of 9,81 square kilometres; the sea marks its northern border, while [[Gijón]] lies to the west, [[Quintes]] to the east and [[San Miguel de Arroes]] to the south.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
Quintueles has ten subdivisions: * San Clemente * Cerredo * Capellanía * Cazamular * La Corolla * El Peñucal * Friuz * Granderroble * Rodavigo * Los Pisones
==Local economy== The Quintueles community has been dedicated to agriculture and stockbreeding for generations, but the modern trend is displaying growth in the service sector.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
Many find the appeal of Quintueles to be its convenient location—it is near a large city, but the distance is great enough to maintain a pastoral atmosphere. This theory, however, is simply speculation.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
==Wildlife== The landscape of Quintueles is dominated by cultivated fields and orchards in the plains zones. Quintueles also has forests of [[eucalyptus]], with a few native [[laurels]], [[chestnut|chestnut trees]], [[oak]]s, and [[hazelnut|hazelnut trees]]. [[Fern]]s, [[furzes]], and [[Blackberry|brambles]] may also be found in thickets.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
This area is filled with animals typically found in coastal regions. Marine birds, namely [[seagull]]s and [[hawk]]s, are common. Migratory birds such as [[swallow]]s, [[thrushes]] and [[starling]]s are also present. [[Weasel]]s, [[squirrel]]s, [[boar]]s, and [[fox]]es are found in the forests.{{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
